[[General (United Kingdom)|General]] '''Sir Peter Mervyn Hunt''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|GCB|DSO|OBE|DL}} (11 March 1916 – 2 October 1988) was [[Chief of the General Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the General Staff]], the professional head of the [[British Army]], from 1973 to 1976. He served in the [[Second World War]] and commanded British Forces deployed in response to the [[Indonesia–Malaysia confrontation]]. Later in his career he provided advice to the British Government at a time of continuing tension associated with [[the Troubles]] in [[Northern Ireland]].

==Army career==
[[File:Wellington College South Front.jpg|thumb|left|Wellington College, where Hunt was educated]]
Son of H. V. Hunt and educated at [[Wellington College, Berkshire|Wellington College]] and the [[Royal Military College, Sandhurst]],<ref name=WW>''Who was Who 1981–1990'', A & C Black Publishers Ltd, 21 November 1991, ISBN 978-0-7136-3336-8</ref> Hunt was commissioned into the [[Queen's Own Cameron Highlanders]] on 30 January 1936.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=34251|supp=|startpage=672|date=31 January 1936|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> Hunt saw action during the [[World War II|Second World War]] and was promoted to [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] on 30 January 1944.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=36353|supp=yes|startpage=571|date=28 January 1944|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> Later that year he was given the temporary rank of [[lieutenant colonel]] and appointed [[Commanding Officer]] of the [[Seaforth Highlanders]],<ref name=WW/> leading them in North West Europe and receiving the [[Distinguished Service Order]] on 10 May 1945.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=37072|supp=yes|startpage=2451|date=8 May 1945|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> After the war he was appointed a Chevalier of the [[Order of Leopold II]] of Belgium and [[Croix de guerre (Belgium)|Croix de guerre]].<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=38079|supp=yes|startpage=4519|date=23 September 1947|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref>

Appointed an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] in the [[New Year Honours]] 1948,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=38161|supp=yes|startpage=10|date=30 December 1947|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> he was given the substantive rank of [[major]] on 30 June 1949<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=38526|supp=yes|startpage=567|date=1 February 1949|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> and became an instructor at the [[Staff College, Camberley]] from 1952<ref name=WW/> and then an instructor at the [[Royal College of Defence Studies|Imperial Defence College]] from 1956<ref name=WW/> before being promoted to lieutenant colonel on 7 June 1957<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=41153|supp=yes|startpage=4915|date=16 August 1957|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> and being given command of the 1st Battalion of the Queen's Own Cameron Highlanders.<ref name=WW/> Promoted to [[Colonel (United Kingdom)|colonel]] on 7 March 1960,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=42016|supp=yes|startpage=2957|date=22 April 1960|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> he became Commander of [[152nd Infantry Brigade (United Kingdom)|152nd (Highland) Infantry Brigade]] in 1960 and Chief of Staff at [[Scottish Command]] in 1962.<ref name=WW/>
[[File:RMAS18Je6-4617.jpg|thumb|left|Hunt served as Commandant of the Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]]
Hunt was appointed [[General Officer Commanding]] the [[17th Gurkha Division]] and Land Forces Borneo<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=43235|supp=yes|startpage=1049|date=31 January 1964|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> and promoted to [[major general]] on 1 February 1964<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=43256|supp=yes|startpage=1845|date=25 February 1964|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> (the post was redesignated 17th Gurkha Division and Malaya District from 1 December 1965 when the [[Indonesia–Malaysia confrontation]] drew to a close).<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=43849|supp=yes|startpage=12165|date=24 December 1965|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> For his service in [[Borneo]] he was appointed a [[Companion of the Order of the Bath]].<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=43837|supp=yes|startpage=11675|date=10 December 1965|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> He was appointed [[List of Governors and Commandants of Sandhurst|Commandant of the Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]] on 19 January 1966<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=43880|supp=yes|startpage=901|date=21 January 1966|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> and went on to be [[General Officer Commanding]] [[British Far East Command|Far East Land Forces]] with the rank of [[lieutenant general]] on 16 November 1968.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=44736|supp=yes|startpage=13509|date=13 December 1968|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> Advanced to [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]] in the [[New Year Honours]] 1969,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=44740|supp=yes|startpage=2|date=20 December 1968|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> he became Commander [[Northern Army Group]] and [[Commander-in-Chief]] of the [[British Army of the Rhine]] with the rank of [[General (United Kingdom)|general]] on 1 December 1970.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=45240|supp=yes|startpage=13110|date=27 November 1970|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> Advanced to [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]] in the [[New Year Honours]] 1973<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=45860|supp=yes|startpage=2|date=29 December 1972|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> and also appointed [[ADC General]] to [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]] that year,<ref name=WW/> Hunt was appointed [[Chief of the General Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the General Staff]] on 19 July 1973<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=46046|supp=yes|startpage=9395|date=7 August 1973|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> at a time of continuing tension associated with [[the Troubles]] in [[Northern Ireland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/november/21/newsid_2549000/2549953.stm |title=1974: Birmingham pub blasts kill 19|publisher=BBC News|date=21 November 1974|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> He retired from the [[British Army]] on 12 August 1976.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=46989|supp=yes|startpage=11249|date=16 August 1976|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref>

He was also Colonel of the [[Queen's Own Highlanders (Seaforth and Camerons)]] from 7 February 1966<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=43892|supp=yes|startpage=1400|date=4 February 1966|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> and Colonel of the [[10th Princess Mary's Own Gurkha Rifles]] from 1 August 1966.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=44069|supp=yes|startpage=8608|date=29 July 1966|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref>

In retirement he became [[Constable of the Tower of London]] from 1 August 1980<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=48272|supp=|startpage=11159|date=6 August 1980|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> and [[Deputy Lieutenant]] of [[Cornwall]] from 4 August 1982.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=49080|supp=|startpage=10532|date=12 August 1982|accessdate=25 December 2011}}</ref> He lived at [[Portloe]] in [[Cornwall]].<ref name=WW/>

His personal interests included [[shooting]] and medical charities: he was President of the [[National Smallbore Rifle Association]] and Chairman of the Council of the [[King Edward VII's Hospital Sister Agnes|King Edward VII's Hospital]] in [[London]].<ref name=WW/> He died on 2 October 1988.<ref name=WW/>

==Family==
In 1940 he married Anne Stopford; they had one son and one daughter.<ref name=WW/> Following the death of his first wife he married Susan Davidson in 1978.<ref name=WW/>

